			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">It has to be a timing thing. Apparently Maniac Mansion waits for a sprite hit to detect the end of the text area at the top, changes the scroll, then uses a timed loop during the whole gameplay area, and finally changes the scroll again for the actions and items. It's only after this last split that the game logic begins.<br /><br />If the top split (which happens after the sprite 0 hit) is correct, there must be something off about the timing of your instructions that is causing the wait loop to finish way too early.<br /><br />I found it pretty interesting that such a small portion of the screen is actually used for computing game logic, while most of the time is spent just waiting. I guess that this kind of game doesn't need that much processing, which is why the developers got away with it.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

